# AGENTS.md

This file provides guidance to AI coding agents (Claude Code, Codex, Gemini CLI, Cursor, etc.) when working with code in this repository. `CLAUDE.md` imports this file, so keep all agent guidance here — single source of truth.

## Project

<!-- EDIT: 2-4 lines: what this system does and for whom. Keep the stack paragraph below. -->
_TODO: one-paragraph description of the project._

Built on SoftLogic's internal `csgt/*` package suite (`csgt/cancerbero` route-based RBAC, `csgt/menu` auto-generated AdminLTE sidebar, `csgt/crud` CRUD base controllers, `csgt/utils` helpers and scaffolding commands). Runs on nginx + php-fpm inside Docker, PHP {{PHP_VERSION}}. See `README.md` for full setup/architecture docs and `vendor/csgt/*/README.md` for each package's own notes.

## Commands

Artisan commands run inside the `php` container: `docker compose exec php <command>`. The `php` container image does not bundle Composer or Node — composer and npm run on the host.

```bash
# Environment setup (first time only)
cp .env.example .env && cp docker-compose.yml.example docker-compose.yml
composer install
docker compose up -d --build
docker compose exec php php artisan key:generate
docker compose exec php php artisan migrate

# Tests
docker compose exec php vendor/bin/phpunit
docker compose exec php vendor/bin/phpunit --filter=TestName   # single test

# Frontend (run on host, not in container)
npm install
npm run watch       # Laravel Mix dev build with watching
npm run production  # production bundle
```

If `APP_ENV=production` in `.env`, destructive Artisan commands (`migrate`, `db:seed`) require `--force`. Set `APP_ENV=local` in your own `.env` for local work.

Bash aliases baked into the `php` image: `migrate`, `rollback`, `seed`, `seedgod` (= `db:seed --class=GodSeeder`), `cda` (= `composer dump-autoload`).

## Conventions

- **Commits**: simple, single-line Conventional Commits, in English (`feat: ...`, `fix: ...`, `chore: ...`). Add a body only when the change truly needs explaining. Never add co-author lines — human or AI.
- **Migrations**: use descriptive names. Never write logic in `down()` — leave it empty. To undo a migration that already ran, write a **new** migration that reverts it, rather than editing/rolling back the old one; this keeps a full, linear history of schema changes.
- **Don't reinvent the wheel**: before writing new logic, check what Laravel core and the `csgt/*` packages already provide (base CRUD controllers, `csgt/utils` helpers, Eloquent features) and use that first.
- **Keep code simple and concise**: prefer the most direct expression of the logic — don't write five lines where Laravel/PHP idioms let you write one.
- **Match the existing code style**: this generation of projects has no automated formatter; follow the formatting, naming and idioms of the surrounding code, and run the project's fixer/static analysis if one is configured.
- **Always enforce the ACL**: every new protected route/catalog must go through the cancerbero/god middleware and have its matching permission registered. Never skip it, even for routes that feel low-risk.
- **Routes mirror where the code lives**: a resource's URL segment must reflect its controller/folder, e.g. `catalogs/clients` ↔ `Catalogs\ClientsController`. Don't nest or rename routes in a way that hides which controller handles them.
- **Handle errors the Laravel-native way**: prefer Form Requests (auto 422), Route Model Binding (auto 404), Policies/Gates (auto 403) and typed Exception classes over manual `if`/`try-catch` blocks that hand-build error responses. Reserve `try/catch` for things Laravel can't handle for you (external API calls, file I/O).
- **Always add timestamps**: every new table needs `$table->timestamps()` for auditability.
- **Write Feature tests for every catalog/endpoint**, covering at least: guest → redirected to login; authenticated but unauthorized → blocked; authorized → 200 on index; store with valid data persists (FK fields validated with `exists:table,id`, not just `required`); store with missing required field → validation error and nothing persisted; update persists the change; destroy removes the row.
- **Generated files are regenerated, not hand-edited**: `.github/workflows/ci.yml` (`make:csgtci`), `dockerfiles/` and `docker-compose.yml` (`make:csgtdocker`), `README.md`, `AGENTS.md` and `CLAUDE.md` skeletons (`make:csgtdocs`).
- **Validation is always server-side**: every input goes through Form Requests / `validationRules`. Frontend validation is UX only — never the security boundary.
- **Eloquent discipline**: eager-load relations with `with()` (no N+1 queries), never run queries inside loops, use `chunk()`/`cursor()` for large datasets.
- **Money is `decimal`, never float**; dates always go through Carbon (no string date math).
- **Language split**: code, comments and commits in English; user-facing strings (titles, labels, validation messages) in Spanish.

## Agent workflow

- **Before every commit**: run the test suite (`vendor/bin/phpunit` — at minimum the tests covering what you changed, the full suite when feasible) and the project's code-style fixer/static analysis if configured. Remove any leftover `dd()`, `dump()`, `ray()` or `console.log`.
- **Atomic commits**: one logical change per commit; don't mix refactors with features. Commit only what the task asked for — no drive-by changes.
- **Ask before destructive operations** (`migrate:fresh`, `migrate:rollback`, `db:wipe`, dropping tables, bulk deletes) and never run them against a non-local database.
- **Never commit secrets**: `.env` stays local; credentials come from env vars, never hardcoded in code or config.
- **Dependencies are surgical**: never run blanket `composer update`/`npm update`; add or update only the package the task requires and commit the lockfile change together with the code that needs it. Mind the PHP {{PHP_VERSION}} / Laravel version constraints of this legacy project.
- **Don't create unrequested files**: no extra markdown docs, helper scripts or examples unless asked; documentation lives in `README.md` and this file.
- **Out-of-scope bugs**: when you spot a bug outside the current task, don't fix it silently and don't ignore it — report it to the user, who decides whether to open a GitHub Issue.

## Architecture

### ACL

Modules, routes, menu entries and permissions are data-driven; roles join to module permissions and the cancerbero middleware checks the current route against the authenticated user's permissions. A god/backdoor role gets every permission via `GodSeeder`.

**To add a new catalog/module**: create the controller under `app/Http/Controllers/Catalogs/` extending the matching `csgt/crud`/`csgt/utils` base controller, register the resource route inside the protected route group, add the model/migration, register the module/permissions the way this project does it, then re-seed and grant access.

<!-- EDIT: document where THIS project declares its modules/permissions/menu and the exact re-seed steps. If this Architecture section outgrows the file, extract it to docs/ARCHITECTURE.md and leave a summary + pointer here. -->

### Runtime

- Docker services: `nginx` (port 80), `php` (php-fpm), `scheduler` and `horizon` (artisan workers via `CONTAINER_ROLE`), `mysql` (port 33061→3306), `redis` (internal only). `DB_HOST=mysql` in `.env` must match the compose service name.
- php-fpm caches opcode: restart the `php` container after significant backend changes if they don't seem to apply.

### Frontend

Vue 2 (SFCs) + AdminLTE, built with Laravel Mix (Node {{NODE_VERSION}}).

